    "body": "I think the most prominent example you are referring to is go-ethereum (and perhaps turbogeth), but I am not really aware of any popular smart contract tooling written in Go. The market leaders (Truffle, Remix, and Hardhat -- see [our survey](https://blog.soliditylang.org/2021/01/26/solidity-developer-survey-2020-results/)) are written in Typescript/Javascript.\r\n\r\nDo you have an example of popular a Go-based framework? Or can you explain what process do you imagine where some end-to-end verification can take place while staying within the the Go ecosystem?",
